         <div type="translation" xml:space="preserve"><head>Translations</head>
            <div type="translation" source="#jmr-jbwp-rgg2003" xml:lang="en"><p>God, Christ, give life to Samphodion, the founder of this workshop. He made it as his own memorial.</p></div>
            </div>
         
         <div type="commentary">
            <head>Commentary</head>
            <p>There are no superscript bars above abbreviated words. </p>
            <p>Line 1 Cf. the <foreign xml:lang="grc">δὸς ζοήν</foreign> in the church of the Apostles at Madeba, dated in 578-9 and the long discussion by 
                    M. Noth in Zeitschrift des Deutschen Palastina Vernis, 84 (1968) 133. 
                    Noth argues from the combination of <foreign xml:lang="grc">Ζοή</foreign> with <foreign xml:lang="grc">ὑγιεία</foreign> in a number os syrian inscriptions that the prayer is essentially for eartly life, 
                    but more complex spiritual concept may also have been involved. cf the discussion of <foreign xml:lang="grc">Ζωή</foreign> and <foreign xml:lang="grc">Ζάω</foreign> in Kittel, Theological Dictionray of the New Testament. </p>
            <p>Line 4 An unusual word to describe a tomb, normally meaning a workshop ('atelier', Robert);  the chamber contained an olive press which may perhaps be an original feature.</p>
         </div>
         
